07263nam a22008655i 9780520921177DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209211777 a10.1525/97805209211772doi  a(DE-B1597)649029  a(OCoLC)1414456414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML198.5b.D75 1999eb 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a780/.943/09732211 aBrinkmann/Wolff, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDriven into Paradise :bThe Musical Migration from Nazi Germany to the United States /cBrinkmann/Wolff; ed. by Reinhold Brinkmann, Christoph Wolff. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (386 p.) :b7 music examples , 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tPREFACE -- tPART ONE Introductory Thoughts -- tReading a Letter -- t"We miss our Jews" The Musical Migration from Nazi Germany -- tPART TWO Experiences, Reports, and Reflections -- tMy Vienna Triangle at Washington Square Revisited and Dilated -- tDisplaced Musics and Immigrant Musicologists: Ethnomusicological and Biographical Perspectives -- tMusic and Musicians in Exile: The Romantic Legacy of a Double Life -- tThe Exile of European Music: Documentation of Upheaval and Immigration in the New York Times -- tPART THREE Acculturation and Identity -- tComposers in Exile: The Question of Musical Identity -- tChallenges and Opportunities of Acculturation: Schoenberg, Krenek, and Stravinsky in Exile -- tReading Whitman/ Responding to America: Hindemith, Weill, and Others -- tPART FOUR Case Studies: Individuals, Places, and Institutions -- tA Viennese Opera Composer in Hollywood: Korngold's Double Exile in America -- tStrangers in Strangers' Land: Werfel, Weill, and The Eternal Road -- tHindemith and Weill: Cases of "Inner" and "Other" Direction -- tWolpe and Black Mountain College -- tFrom Jewish Exile in Germany to German Scholar in America: Alfred Einstein's Emigration -- tImmigrant Musicians and the American Chamber Music Scene, 1930—1950 -- tAPPENDIX Musicologists Who Emigrated from Germany, Austria, and Central Europe, ca. 1930-1945 -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe forced migration of artists and scholars from Nazi Germany is a compelling and often wrenching story. The story is twofold, of impoverishment for the countries the musicians left behind and enrichment for the United States. The latter is the focus of this eminent collection, which approaches the subject from diverse perspectives, including documentary-style newspaper accounts and an exploration of Walt Whitman's poetry in the work of Paul Hindemith and Kurt Weill.The flood of musical migration from Germany and Austria from 1933 to 1944 had a lasting impact. Hundreds of musicians and musicologists came to the United States and remained here, and the shaping power of their talents is incalculable. Several essays provide firsthand insights into aspects of American cultural history to which these émigrés made essential contributions as conductors, professors, and composers; other essays tell of the traumatic experience of being exiled and the difficulties of finding one's way in a foreign country. While the migration infused the U.S. with a distinctly European musical awareness, at the same time the status and authority of its participants tended to intervene in the development of a genuinely American cultural voice. The story of the unprecedented migration that resulted from Nazism has many dimensions, and Driven Into Paradise illuminates them in deeply human terms.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExilesxHistor